Using Vieta's formulas, if the roots are \( p \) and \( q \), then: \[ p + q = -k \quad \text{and} \quad pq = 36 \] We need to find all pairs of integers \( (p, q) \) such that their product is 36 and they are distinct. The factor pairs of 36 (both positive and negative) are: \[ (1, 36), (2, 18), (3, 12), (4, 9), (-1, -36), (-2, -18), (-3, -12), (-4, -9) \] For each pair, we calculate \( k \) as \( -(p + q) \): - For \( (1, 36) \), \( k = -(1 + 36) = -37 \) - For \( (2, 18) \), \( k = -(2 + 18) = -20 \) - For \( (3, 12) \), \( k = -(3 + 12) = -15 \) - For \( (4, 9) \), \( k = -(4 + 9) = -13 \) - For \( (-1, -36) \), \( k = -(-1 + (-36)) = 37 \) - For \( (-2, -18) \), \( k = -(-2 + (-18)) = 20 \) - For \( (-3, -12) \), \( k = -(-3 + (-12)) = 15 \) - For \( (-4, -9) \), \( k = -(-4 + (-9)) = 13 \) The distinct values of \( k \) are \( \pm 13, \pm 15, \pm 20, \pm 37 \), resulting in 8 distinct values. Thus, the number of values of \( k \) is \(\boxed{8}\).
